    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>15 Marine Parade | Eastbourne</placeName>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>This is my address.—   I will write soon— I am grateful for your last note.—</p>
<p>I am dying to hear about pure gum<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p><hi rend="italic">[</hi>Yours<hi rend="italic">]</hi> | C. Darwin.</p>
<p>P.S.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> | Will you be so kind as to dry a little of your Gum used on Drosera &amp; burn it; perhaps you would detect smell of animal matter if any gelatine or glue used or size<ref target="#foot.f4"/> used.—</p>
<p>Any corrosive Sublimate??<ref target="#foot.f5"/></p>
<p>Could you send me, when you write, one leaf (&amp; name) of Australian Drosera, that I may see it out of idle curiosity.—<ref target="#foot.f6"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>
                <div type="tnotes">
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n1">4.1 of] <hi rend="italic">before del</hi> ‘the’</note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n2">4.1 your] <hi rend="italic">added</hi></note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n3">4.3 .—-] <hi rend="italic">added, pencil</hi></note>
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n4">5.1 Any corrosive Sublimate??] <hi rend="italic">added, pencil</hi></note>
                </div>

            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Dated by CD’s reference to having arrived in Eastbourne. CD and the children left Down on 22 September (‘Journal’; Appendix II). The letter was written prior to receiving Oliver’s reply (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2927.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Daniel Oliver, 25 September 1860</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See preceding letter and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2921.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Daniel Oliver, 19 September 1860</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">The postscript is on a separate slip of paper. The contents indicate that it belongs to this letter.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Size: ‘an agglutinant consisting of undried glue’ (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2248.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">EB</hi></ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">This sentence was added in pencil.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-2913.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to Daniel Oliver, 11 September [1860]</ref>. There is a note headed ‘Drosera spathulata Australia from Kew’ that is dated ‘Sept. 28<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>—/60/’ in DAR 54: 5.</note>
        </div>        
            
